SIMPLE: poke
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Poke
<hw>Poke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A large
North American herb of the genus <gen>Phytolacca</gen> (<spn>Phytolacca
decandra</spn>), bearing dark purple juicy berries; -- called also
<altname>garget</altname>, <altname>pigeon berry</altname>,
<altname>pocan</altname>, and <altname>pokeweed</altname>. The root and
berries have emetic and purgative properties, and are used in medicine.
The young shoots are sometimes eaten as a substitute for asparagus, and
the berries are said to be used in Europe to color wine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Poke
<hw>Poke</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>poca</ets>, <ets>poha</ets>,
<ets>pohha</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>poki</ets>, OD. <ets>poke</ets>,
and perh. to E. <ets>pock</ets>; cf. also Gael. <ets>poca</ets>, and OF.
<ets>poque</ets>. Cf. <er>Pock</er>, <er>Pocket</er>,
<er>Pouch</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bag; a sack; a pocket.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧He drew a dial from his <xex>poke</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They wallowed as pigs in a <qex>poke</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A long, wide sleeve; -- called also <altname>poke
sleeve</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To boy a pig a poke</b></col><cd> (that is, in a bag), to
buy a thing without knowledge or examination of it.</cd>
<rj><au>Camden.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Poke
<hw>Poke</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Poked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Poking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. LG. <ets>poken</ets> to
prick, pierce, thrust, <ets>pok</ets> a dagger, knife, D.
<ets>pook</ets>, G. <ets>pocken</ets> to beat, also Ir. <ets>poc</ets> a
blow, Gael. <ets>puc</ets> to push.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To thrust or
push against or into with anything pointed; hence, to stir up; to
excite; <as>as, to <ex>poke</ex> a fire</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>poked</qex> John, and said ⟦ldquo⟧Sleepest thou
?⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To thrust with the horns; to gore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[From 5th <er>Poke</er>, 3.]</ety> <def>To put a
poke on; <as>as, to <ex>poke</ex> an ox</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To poke fun</b></col>, <cd>to excite fun; to joke; to
jest.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To poke fun at</b></col>,
<cd>to make a butt of; to ridicule.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Poke
<hw>Poke</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To search; to feel one's way, as in
the dark; to grope; <as>as, to <ex>poke</ex> about</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man must have <qex>poked</qex> into Latin and Greek.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Poke
<hw>Poke</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of poking; a
thrust; a jog; <as>as, a <ex>poke</ex> in the ribs</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Ld. Lytton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A lazy person; a dawdler; also, a stupid or
uninteresting person.</def> <mark>[Slang, U.S.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A contrivance to prevent an animal from leaping or
breaking through fences. It consists of a yoke with a pole inserted,
pointed forward.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Poke bonnet</b></col>, <cd>a bonnet with a straight,
projecting front.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pokebag</ent>⟦br⟧
